data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **span overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(x)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent `Span`/`ReadOnlySpan` parameters (they're ref structs), so this throws at runtime.

## Fix

Force the compiler to resolve to the `Enumerable` overload by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Before (breaks in .NET 10 / C# 14)
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.Contains(num);

// Fix option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Fix option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches ensure the `IEnumerable<T>` overload is selected, which expression trees can represent. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — it now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension returning `void` instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`.
